<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">check made the Sioux move cautious in their proceedings ever since.  The stockades which surround the villages are principally collected from drift wood and have a miserable appearance but which as I understand can at a short notice be put into a tolerable state of defence as every individual lends a hand.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This afternoon we observed a common diversion of these nations which is running races on foot.  For this purpose they assemble upon a beautiful green near the village whence the set out stark naked across the hills; return by a different route covered with dust and sweat plunge into the river<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This race takes at least Six to perform &#8211; and it is a matter of surprise to see the distance that some of them gain over others<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[D]</span>uring this Exercise the heat was so excessive that we could not resist it in the open air but were under the necessity of seeking shelter under a shade<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">During my absence Yesterday my people who had remained were present at a horse race.  The Indians assembled on horseback about three miles from the <span class="AddHand-author">Village</span>, whence they set out in a body</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">-pell-</p>

